We know that $\cos 300^\circ = \cos(360^\circ - 60^\circ)$. By the cosine difference formula, we have:

\begin{align*}
\cos(360^\circ - 60^\circ) &= \cos 360^\circ \cos 60^\circ + \sin 360^\circ \sin 60^\circ \\
&= \cos 60^\circ \\
&= \boxed{\frac{1}{2}}
\end{align*}

First, we need to find an angle between 0 and 360 degrees that is coterminal with 300 degrees. We can do this by subtracting 360 degrees as many times as needed until we get an angle between 0 and 360 degrees. 

$300^\circ - 360^\circ = -60^\circ$

$-60^\circ + 360^\circ = 300^\circ$

So, $\cos 300^\circ = \cos(-60^\circ)$. 

Since the cosine function has a period of $360^\circ$, we know that $\cos(-60^\circ) = \cos(300^\circ)$.

We can use the unit circle to find the cosine of $-60^\circ$. 

If we draw a line from the origin to the point on the unit circle that is $60^\circ$ counterclockwise from the positive $x$-axis, we form a 30-60-90 triangle. 

[asy]
size(5cm);
draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));
draw((-1.2,0)--(1.2,0),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));
draw((0,0)--(sqrt(3)/2,-0.5)--(sqrt(3)/2,0.5)--cycle,dashed);
draw((0,0)--(cos(-60),sin(-60)),thick);
draw((1,0)--(cos(-60),0)--(cos(-60),sin(-60)),dashed);

label("$x$",(1.2,0),SE);
label("$y$",(0,1.2),NE);
label("$1$",(1,0.5));
label("$\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$",(sqrt(3)/2,0));
label("$\frac{1}{2}$",(sqrt(3)/4,-0.25));
label("$-60^\circ$",(0.6,-0.2));
[/asy]

Since the hypotenuse of this triangle has length 1, we know that the side opposite $-60^\circ$ has length $\frac{1}{2}$ and the side adjacent to $-60^\circ$ has length $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$. 

Therefore, $\cos(-60^\circ) = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$. 

So, $\cos 300^\circ = \cos(-60^\circ) = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$. 

The answer is $\boxed{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}$.

